  "output": "Here's the full performance analysis. The codebase is early-stage, so several categories are clean by default — I'll be honest about that and focus on the real findings.\n\n---\n\n## Performance Analysis\n\n### 1. N+1 Query Patterns\n\n**No N+1 today, but a trap is already set.**\n\nThe `events` table has no index on `tenant_id`:\n\n```sql\n-- migrations/20260711040112_create_events_table.sql\n-- Missing:\nCREATE INDEX idx_events_tenant_id ON events(tenant_id);\n```\n\nThe Phase 1 status says GET /events is missing. When you add it, the obvious query will be `WHERE tenant_id = $1` — and without that index, every call is a full table scan. Add the index in a new migration now, before the data grows.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Auth Middleware — DB Hit on Every Request (most impactful)\n\n`middleware/auth.rs:30` hits Postgres on **every single request** to validate an API key. At any meaningful ingest volume this becomes the bottleneck.\n\n```rust\n// This runs for every POST /events\nlet row = sqlx::query_as::<_, (String,)>(\n    \"SELECT tenant_id FROM api_keys WHERE key_hash = $1\",\n)\n.fetch_optional(&pool).await\n```\n\nAPI keys are nearly static data — they change rarely. The fix is an in-memory cache:\n\n```rust\n// In main.rs, add shared state:\nuse std::collections::HashMap;\nuse std::sync::Arc;\nuse tokio::sync::RwLock;\n\ntype ApiKeyCache = Arc<RwLock<HashMap<String, String>>>; // key_hash -> tenant_id\n\n// Pass it into the middleware alongside the pool.\n// In require_api_key: check cache first, only hit DB on miss, then populate cache.\n```\n\nA `DashMap` is even better for concurrent reads (no write-lock contention). For production, Redis gives you cross-instance consistency when you scale horizontally.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Connection Pool Too Small\n\n`main.rs:19`:\n\n```rust\n.max_connections(5)\n```\n\nAn event ingestion platform is write-heavy. At 5 connections, under any real load requests will queue waiting for a pool slot. A good default is `num_cpus * 2` or at minimum 20 for I/O-bound workloads. Raise this to at least 20 and expose it as an env var:\n\n```rust\nlet max_conn: u32 = std::env::var(\"DB_POOL_MAX\")\n    .ok()\n    .and_then(|v| v.parse().ok())\n    .unwrap_or(20);\n\nPgPoolOptions::new().max_connections(max_conn)\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. No Batch Insert Support\n\n`handlers/events.rs:18` inserts one event per HTTP request:\n\n```rust\nsqlx::query(\"INSERT INTO events (tenant_id, event_type) VALUES ($1, $2)\")\n    .execute(&pool).await\n```\n\nFor an analytics ingest platform the expected pattern is high-frequency writes. Consider a `/events/batch` endpoint that takes `Vec<EventInput>` and issues a single multi-row insert:\n\n```sql\nINSERT INTO events (tenant_id, event_type)\nSELECT $1, unnest($2::text[])\n```\n\nThis drastically reduces round-trips per unit of work.\n\n---\n\n### 5. React / Frontend\n\nThe frontend is the default Vite template (`App.tsx`). There are no data fetching, no component trees, no state management — nothing to flag in the re-renders, memory leaks, or redundant computation categories. These will become relevant in Phase 3+ when you build the actual dashboard UI.\n\n---\n\n## Priority Order\n\n| # | Finding | Impact | Effort |\n|---|---------|--------|--------|\n| 1 | Cache API key lookups (skip DB on every request) | High | Medium |\n| 2 | Add `idx_events_tenant_id` migration now | High | Low |\n| 3 | Raise connection pool to 20+ | Medium | Low |\n| 4 | Batch insert endpoint for Phase 3+ | Medium | Medium |\n\nThe cache is the one to do first — it pays dividends immediately and the pattern will apply again when you add more auth tiers.\n",
